{"id":14880741,"mediaExerciseId":"733a1ef4-d083-4674-9e1c-9c2e8ac7f038","exerciseName":"2","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612264,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":42,"solutions":[{"id":5971864,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we will determine why revenues and expenses appearing in an income statement may differ from cash flows occurring in a specific period.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/919cbd9c3c11503545b94ea63e5359e8/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/919cbd9c3c11503545b94ea63e5359e8/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The income statement shows the **revenues earned and expenses incurred** in one accounting period. Its bottom-line will determine whether the operations are profitable or not - through net income/net loss computation.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":107,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/a279f7137bc257e8f1dd1c4ebce3d508/lateximg_large.png","width":1029},"regular":{"height":54,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/a279f7137bc257e8f1dd1c4ebce3d508/lateximg.png","width":516}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Following Generally Accepted Accounting Standards (GAAP), entities should **recognize revenues when earned and expenses as incurred**. According to the accrual basis of accounting, regardless of cash flows, the income and expense recognition should follow the timing of completion - upon service rendition or product delivery.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/122a214941bb8422fc058c60f6290e83/lateximg_large.png","width":1008},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/122a214941bb8422fc058c60f6290e83/lateximg.png","width":503}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"For instance, an entity rendering service will earn income for the current year but receive a cash payment in the following year. Similarly, a business would incur utilities, such as water and electricity expenses, but settle its bills next year.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/6a27b74da941dbfd5cbb7c9d553b65ba/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/6a27b74da941dbfd5cbb7c9d553b65ba/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"To avoid confusion, we should understand how an entity recognizes income and expenses in its books and cash moving in and out of business. Revenue and expense recognition follows **accrual accounting**, while cash flows follow **actual receipts and disbursements**.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/f20592f7f269541bb1a2be87f460fcb8/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/bc39f436cf2ad02ec2f211392f893583/f20592f7f269541bb1a2be87f460fcb8/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"aa2663ba-17d7-4ac3-a99c-729d3e6769bf","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5},{"id":5898030,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to explain why the revenue and cost figures shown on a standard income statement may not represent the actual cash inflows and outflows. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The main reason why the revenue and cost figures shown on a standard income statement may not be representative of the actual cash inflows and outflows that occurred during the period is the **revenue recognition and matching principle.** \n\nThe revenue recognition principle states that companies recognize revenue as it is earned not when they received cash. \n\nThe matching principle requires that revenue and any related expenses should be recognized in the same period in which the corresponding revenue is earned. \n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":97,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/4a87502d42f9da3ac828c97cff1ed1a2/58b290eb6d3cf9b944e55659db8942ac/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":50,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/4a87502d42f9da3ac828c97cff1ed1a2/58b290eb6d3cf9b944e55659db8942ac/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"f070d1ce-e63a-4ade-bffe-7162d3150f08","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880742,"exerciseName":"3","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"ab818ea2-a7ac-4340-a63a-6a4cf8a95912","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-3-ab818ea2-a7ac-4340-a63a-6a4cf8a95912"},{"id":14880743,"exerciseName":"4","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"a2a2189f-6fee-4411-8f79-b9a0e5dd5c93","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-4-a2a2189f-6fee-4411-8f79-b9a0e5dd5c93"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880740,"exerciseName":"1","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"5d03328a-ad6f-4295-8608-d4c0bb984c32","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-1-5d03328a-ad6f-4295-8608-d4c0bb984c32"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-2-733a1ef4-d083-4674-9e1c-9c2e8ac7f038"}